To scan for drones, you typically don't need a specific wireless adapter. However, having a wireless adapter that supports monitor mode can greatly enhance your capabilities in detecting and analyzing drone signals.


Monitor mode allows your wireless adapter to capture and analyze all wireless network traffic in the vicinity, including drone signals. This mode enables you to monitor the various drone communication protocols, such as Wi-Fi or other RF frequencies.


To put your wireless adapter into monitor mode, you can use tools like airmon-ng (for Linux) or similar software that supports monitor mode. Here's an example of how you can use airmon-ng to enable monitor mode on a wireless adapter:



Open a terminal or command prompt.

Type sudo airmon-ng start wlan0 (replace wlan0 with the name of your wireless interface).

This command will put your wireless adapter into monitor mode, typically named as wlan0mon.

You can then use tools like airodump-ng to scan for nearby wireless networks, including drones.


Keep in mind that scanning for drones without proper authorization and legitimate reasons may be illegal and unethical. It is essential to respect the privacy of others and comply with relevant laws and regulations.


